Project: Investigate a Dataset (TMDb movie data)¶

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction
  • Data Wrangling
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

The Movie Database (TMDb) is a community built movie and TV database.
In this presentation, based on this dataset various questions will be answered for the curious minds. The TMDb movie data set cleaned from original data on Kaggle is investigated to answer some questions.

Questions¶

  • Which genres are most popular from year to year?
  • How much the movie genres change from year to year?
  • How many movies based on their genres were produced?
  • Which are some of the top movies based on features like adjusted revenue and budget, popularity.
  • Have revenues increased over time?
  • Do higher revenue films make more profits?

Observations¶

  1. Unit of currency is not mentioned in the dataset. We would take USD as it is the most common de facto global currency.
  2. vote_count is different for different movies, so the popularity of the movies can't be concluded based on the vote_average.

{'Documentary', 'Western', 'Horror', 'Romance', 'Family', 'Thriller', 'Animation', 'Comedy', 'Adventure', 'Music', 'Crime', 'TV Movie', 'Mystery', 'Fantasy', 'Science Fiction', 'History', 'War', 'Foreign', 'Action', 'Drama'}
In [24]:
# Create a dataframe which contains the sum of movies genre per year
genre_count_per_year = pd.DataFrame(index = year_set, columns=genre_set)
genre_count_per_year[:] = 0  

for year in year_set:
    genre_dict = {}
    genres_in_year = genres_and_year[genres_and_year.release_year == year]
    genres_in_year = genres_in_year["genres"].values
    for elem in genres_in_year:
        genres_row = elem.split("|")
        for genre in genres_row:
            if genre not in genre_dict:
                genre_dict[genre] = 1
            else:
                genre_dict[genre] = genre_dict[genre] + 1
                    
    aux_df = pd.DataFrame(genre_dict, index = [year])
    genre_count_per_year.loc[year, aux_df.columns] = genre_count_per_year.loc[year, aux_df.columns] + aux_df.loc[year]

How much the movie genres changes from year to year?¶

In [31]:
# Plot a stacked area plot showing the trend of movie genres over the years
ax = genre_count_per_year.plot.area(stacked=True);
ax.set(xlabel='movie_titles', ylabel='movies_count', title = 'Stacked area plot showing the trend of movie genres over the years')
pt.show()

In general the number of movies and consequently the movie genres show an increase in numbers from 1960 to 2015. It can be seen that the majority of the movie genres show an increasing trend. Drama seems to be the most frequent and pervalent genre in movies through all these years. Other categories such as Thriller, Comedy and Action movies also show a similar pattern.

It can be seen that the movies that do better at the box office have a little less than double the profits as compared to those that make less. Movies under top 100 have profitability ratio of 44% and those in top 100 have profitabiity ratio of 82% which shows an increase of 38%.
So it can be concluded that top revenue movies have higher budgets and much higher profits.

Conclusions¶

Summary¶

  • Since 1960, Drama has been the most popular genre except for some years when Comedy and Thriller was more poular.
  • Drama, Comedy, Thriller and Action are the most popular genres over the years 1960-2015 and make up about 50% of all the movies.
  • Top 5 movies from the given dataset based on their adjusted revenues are; Avatar, Star Wars, Titanic, The Exorcist and Jaws.
  • Top 5 movies from the given dataset based on their adjusted budgets are; The Warrior's Way, Pirates of the Caribbean: On Stranger Tides, Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's Ends, Superman Returns, Titanic.
  • Top 5 movies from the given dataset based on their adjusted budgets are; Jurassic World, Mad Max: Fury Road, Interstellar, Guardians of the Galaxy, Insurgent.
  • Revenues over the years have increased from 17 million to 164 million. This shows an increase of 865%.
  • The inflation adjusted revenue has however remained nearly steady over the years.
  • Movies with higher revenues have higher budgets and make much higher profits.
  • Revenue and profitability have a weak positive correlation.

Limitations¶

  • All conclusions are limited to the underlying data set. As no advaned statistics were performed, the results can only be treated as indicators and are not generalizable.
  • Vote count is different for different movies, so the popularity of the movies can't be concluded based on the average votes. This makes the vote_count and vote_average columns to be of no use.
  • Dataset contains null and zero values in some features. These zero and null values hinder the analysis and have to be removed from the rows that correspond to these zero and null values.
  • Many entries in the dataset have been removed due to missing data. If there were more observations in the analysis, the results could be different.
  • Fewer movies were produced in the 20th century than movies produced in the 21st century. This could make the descritive statistics of movies in the past less robust than movies closer to the present.
